    "## One-Hot Encoding for Categorical Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "One-hot encoding was applied to all categorical features\n",
    "in the Train/Test Split cell. Documented here for lesson\n",
    "completeness.\n",
    "\n",
    "### What was encoded\n",
    "| Feature | Original categories | Columns created |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| platform | Google Ads, Meta Ads, TikTok Ads | 2 (drop_first) |\n",
    "| campaign_type | Search, Display, Video, Shopping | 3 (drop_first) |\n",
    "| industry | Fintech, SaaS, Healthcare, EdTech, E-commerce | 4 (drop_first) |\n",
    "| country | USA, UK, UAE, Germany, Canada, India, Australia | 6 (drop_first) |\n",
    "\n",
    "Total binary columns created: 15\n",
    "Original categorical columns: 4\n",
    "Dataset expanded from 9 to 24 columns after encoding\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why drop_first=True\n",
    "Prevents multicollinearity — if a campaign is not Google Ads\n",
    "and not TikTok Ads, it must be Meta Ads. The third column\n",
    "adds no new information and creates redundancy in the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Baseline categories (reference groups in OLS)\n",
    "- platform: Google Ads (baseline)\n",
    "- campaign_type: Display (baseline)\n",
    "- industry: E-commerce (baseline)\n",
    "- country: Australia (baseline)\n",
    "\n",
    "All other categories will be interpreted relative to these\n",
    "baselines in OLS coefficients.\n",
    "\n",
    "### High cardinality check\n",
    "All four categorical features have low to medium cardinality\n",
    "(3-7 categories) — no grouping of rare categories required.\n",
    "Highest cardinality: country with 7 categories — acceptable\n",
    "for one-hot encoding with drop_first=True."
