    "## OLS Regression — Experiment 1 (Baseline Model)\n",
    "\n",
    "### Model specification\n",
    "- Algorithm: Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) via statsmodels\n",
    "- Target: Log-transformed campaign revenue — log(revenue + 1)\n",
    "- Features: 22 features after dropping the month (multicollinearity)\n",
    "- Training set: 1,440 rows\n",
    "- Test set: 360 rows\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why log-transformed revenue\n",
    "Revenue is right-skewed (skewness 2.556). Log transformation\n",
    "reduces skewness to −0.517 — approximating the normal distribution\n",
    "required by OLS. Coefficients represent percentage changes\n",
    "in revenue rather than dollar amounts.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Known limitations going in\n",
    "- Joint multicollinearity confirmed (VIF > 10 for 5 features)\n",
    "- Individual coefficients may be unstable\n",
    "- R² remains valid and interpretable despite high VIF\n",
    "- Experiment 2 will address VIF by dropping high-VIF features\n",
    "\n",
    "### Hypotheses being tested\n",
    "**H₀:** Ad spend, clicks, and conversions have no statistically\n",
    "significant effect on campaign revenue across platforms,\n",
    "industries, and markets.\n",
    "\n",
    "**H₁:** Conversions and clicks are the strongest positive predictors\n",
    "of revenue, with platform type and industry moderating\n",
    "the relationship after controlling for country and seasonality.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Success criteria\n",
    "- R² > 0.70 — model explains the majority of revenue variation\n",
    "- conversions coefficient positive and significant (p < 0.05)\n",
    "- TikTok coefficient positive and significant vs Google baseline\n",
    "- F-statistic significant (p < 0.05) — overall model valid"
   ]
